# Home UI Redesign Phase 1 Specification

## Purpose

Redesign the Home screen presentation to match the provided light/dark references while keeping existing navigation and favorite/search behavior intact.

## Requirements

### Requirement: Home screen shell

The Home screen MUST render a top shell with safe-area padding, a search affordance, an account/avatar affordance, a category chip row, a masonry content region, and the existing bottom tab navigation. A floating add action MAY remain visible if already present in the app shell.

#### Scenario: Shell is visible on first render
- GIVEN the user opens the Home tab
- WHEN the screen finishes initial layout
- THEN the top shell, chip row, content grid, and bottom tabs are visible

#### Scenario: Shell survives theme changes
- GIVEN the Home screen is open
- WHEN the system theme changes
- THEN the overall shell structure remains unchanged

### Requirement: Category chips visual behavior

Category chips MUST present as a horizontal segmented row with one active chip and inactive chips styled with lower emphasis. The active chip MUST be clearly distinguishable in both themes.

#### Scenario: Active chip is highlighted
- GIVEN the default Home screen state
- WHEN the screen renders
- THEN one chip is selected and visually emphasized

#### Scenario: Chip selection is stable
- GIVEN a non-active chip is tapped
- WHEN the selection changes
- THEN the tapped chip becomes active and the previous active chip loses emphasis

### Requirement: Masonry card presentation

Content cards MUST use a staggered masonry presentation with consistent outer spacing, rounded media corners, image-first hierarchy, and text below the image. Favorite and share badges/icons MUST overlay the media without obscuring the primary subject.

#### Scenario: Card hierarchy is readable
- GIVEN a visible content card
- WHEN the card is rendered
- THEN the title is below the image and the subtitle is lower-emphasis text

#### Scenario: Badges remain visible
- GIVEN a card contains favorite/share actions
- WHEN the card is shown
- THEN the badges/icons are visible and positioned within the media bounds

### Requirement: Theme parity

The Home screen MUST support light and dark variants with matched spacing, typography hierarchy, and interactive states. Backgrounds, chip surfaces, text, and icon contrast SHOULD remain legible in both themes.

#### Scenario: Light and dark variants match structure
- GIVEN the app is in light theme
- WHEN compared to dark theme
- THEN both variants preserve the same layout and component order

#### Scenario: Contrast remains usable
- GIVEN either theme is active
- WHEN the user scans the screen
- THEN primary text and icons remain readable against their surfaces

### Requirement: Interaction constraints

The redesign MUST preserve existing favorite behavior, existing search entry behavior, and current navigation routes. The redesign MUST NOT change repository, domain, or data contracts.

#### Scenario: Favorite behavior is preserved
- GIVEN a card supports the existing favorite gesture
- WHEN the user performs that gesture
- THEN the favorite action still works as before

#### Scenario: Search behavior is preserved
- GIVEN the search affordance is visible
- WHEN the user activates it
- THEN the existing search flow is opened without route changes

### Requirement: Non-functional layout and accessibility

The Home screen SHOULD adapt responsively across narrow phones and larger screens, and it MUST avoid clipping critical content. Interactive controls SHOULD expose a minimum accessible touch target and maintain basic contrast for text and icons.

#### Scenario: Small screens remain usable
- GIVEN a narrow device width
- WHEN the screen renders
- THEN the shell, chips, and cards remain usable without overlap

#### Scenario: Wider screens preserve density
- GIVEN a tablet or wide viewport
- WHEN the screen renders
- THEN the masonry layout reflows without breaking the visual hierarchy

## Out of Scope

- No data fetching changes
- No domain, repository, or validation contract changes
- No new search or favorite logic
- No new content model for cards or categories
